<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec-variation-in-real-life" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Variation in Real Life</title>
    <objectives component="outcomes">
        <introduction>
            <p>
            <dl>
                <li>
                    <title>Strand</title>
                    <p>1.0 Numbers and Algebra</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Sub-Strand</title>
                    <p>1.5 Formulae and Variations</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Specific Learning Outcomes</title> 
                    <p>
                        <ul>
                          <li>Apply variations to real life situations</li>
                          <li>Appreciate the use of variations in day-to-day life</li>
                        </ul>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Grade Level</title>
                    <p>11</p>
                </li>
                <li component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Estimated Duration</title>
                    <p>40 minutes</p>
                </li>
            </dl>
            </p>
        </introduction>
    </objectives>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Problem-Solving and Discovery</title>
        <dl>
            <li>
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p>15 minutes</p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Objective</title>
                <p>To visualize how tabular data transforms into linear trends on a graph using local pricing models.</p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Teacher's Role</title>
                <p>Guide learners in plotting the vertical intercept. Ensure they understand that the "Starting Point" on the graph represents fixed costs like standing charges or mobilization fees.</p>
            </li>
        </dl>
    </axiom>

    <activity>
        <statement>
            <p>
                <strong>Activity: From Tables to Graphs</strong>
            </p>
            <p>
                A taxi service in Nairobi charges a base "booking fee" of 200 Ksh and an additional 100 Ksh for every kilometer traveled.
            </p>
            <table>
                <title>Taxi Fare Data</title>
                <tabular halign="center">
                    <row header="yes" bottom="minor">
                        <cell>Distance (<inline-math>d</inline-math>) in km</cell>
                        <cell>0</cell>
                        <cell>2</cell>
                        <cell>4</cell>
                        <cell>6</cell>
                        <cell>8</cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell>Total Cost (<inline-math>C</inline-math>) in Ksh</cell>
                        <cell>200</cell>
                        <cell>400</cell>
                        <cell>600</cell>
                        <cell>800</cell>
                        <cell>1000</cell>
                    </row>
                </tabular>
            </table>
            <p>
                <strong>Steps:</strong>
                <ol>
                    <li>Plot the Total Cost (<inline-math>C</inline-math>) on the vertical axis and Distance (<inline-math>d</inline-math>) on the horizontal axis.</li>
                    <li>Connect the points with a straight line.</li>
                    <li>Identify the point where the line crosses the vertical axis. What does this value represent?</li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </statement>
    </activity>

    <xi:include href="../lesson-plan-templates/example-intro.ptx" />

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p><strong>1. Agribusiness:</strong> The cost of tilling a farm (<inline-math>C</inline-math>) is partly constant and partly varies as the area (<inline-math>A</inline-math>) in acres. If tilling 2 acres costs 4,500 Ksh and 6 acres costs 10,500 Ksh, find the cost of tilling 10 acres.</p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                Let <inline-math>C = kA + b</inline-math>.
                Subtracting the equations <inline-math>10500 = 6k + b</inline-math> and <inline-math>4500 = 2k + b</inline-math> gives <inline-math>4k = 6000</inline-math>, so <inline-math>k = 1500</inline-math>.
                Substitute into the first equation: <inline-math>4500 = 2(1500) + b</inline-math>, so <inline-math>b = 1500</inline-math>.
                For 10 acres: <me>C = 1500(10) + 1500 = 16,500 \text{ Ksh}</me>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p><strong>2. Utility Bills:</strong> A water bill in Nakuru has a fixed standing charge and a variable rate per unit. If 20 units cost 850 Ksh and 35 units cost 1,300 Ksh, calculate the bill for 50 units.</p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                The difference in cost for 15 units is 450 Ksh, so the rate <inline-math>k = 30 \text{ Ksh/unit}</inline-math>.
                Fixed charge <inline-math>b = 850 - 20(30) = 250 \text{ Ksh}</inline-math>.
                For 50 units: <me>C = 30(50) + 250 = 1,750 \text{ Ksh}</me>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p><strong>3. Logistics:</strong> A courier company charges 2,500 Ksh flat for insurance and 150 Ksh per kg for transport. Find the total cost to ship a 45 kg crate.</p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                Equation: <inline-math>T = 150w + 2500</inline-math>.
                For <inline-math>w = 45</inline-math>:
                <me>T = 150(45) + 2500 = 6750 + 2500 = 9,250 \text{ Ksh}</me>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p><strong>4. Construction:</strong> A contractor charges a fixed mobilization fee and a cost per meter to build a stone wall. 10 meters cost 15,000 Ksh, while 25 meters cost 30,000 Ksh. Find the fixed fee.</p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                Difference of 15 meters costs 15,000 Ksh, so <inline-math>k = 1000 \text{ Ksh/m}</inline-math>.
                Using <inline-math>15000 = 10(1000) + b</inline-math>:
                <me>b = 15000 - 10000 = 5,000 \text{ Ksh}</me>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p><strong>5. Employment:</strong> A salesman earns a basic salary plus a 10% commission on sales. If he earns 25,000 Ksh for selling goods worth 100,000 Ksh, find his basic salary.</p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                Commission = <inline-math>0.1 \times 100000 = 10,000 \text{ Ksh}</inline-math>.
                Basic Salary = <inline-math>25000 - 10000 = 15,000 \text{ Ksh}</inline-math>.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <xi:include href="../lesson-plan-templates/assessment-intro.ptx" />

    <exercises>
        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>A printing business charges a fixed setup fee of 3,000 Ksh and 50 Ksh per brochure. Write the equation for the total cost and calculate the cost for 500 brochures.</p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    <me>C = 50n + 3000</me>
                    <me>C = 50(500) + 3000 = 25000 + 3000 = 28,000 \text{ Ksh}</me>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p> A certain borehole drilling company in Kajiado charges a fixed fee of 60,000 Ksh and 3,500 Ksh per meter. If a farmer paid 410,000 Ksh, how deep was the borehole?</p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    <me>410000 = 3500d + 60000</me>
                    <me>350000 = 3500d \text{ so } d = 100 \text{ meters}</me>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>The cost (<inline-math>C</inline-math>) of feeding students at a camp is partly constant and partly varies as the number of students (<inline-math>n</inline-math>). Feeding 50 students costs 12,000 Ksh, while 80 students costs 18,000 Ksh. Find the cost for 120 students.</p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    Difference for 30 students is 6,000 Ksh, so <inline-math>k = 200</inline-math>.
                    <inline-math>b = 12000 - 50(200) = 2,000</inline-math>.
                    For 120 students: <me>C = 200(120) + 2000 = 26,000 \text{ Ksh}</me>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>An internet service provider charges a monthly fee and a rate per GB used. A user pays 1,200 Ksh for 10 GB and 2,000 Ksh for 30 GB. What is the monthly standing charge?</p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    Difference of 20 GB costs 800 Ksh, so <inline-math>k = 40 \text{ Ksh/GB}</inline-math>.
                    Standing charge <inline-math>b = 1200 - 10(40) = 800 \text{ Ksh}</inline-math>.
                </p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>A dairy farmer's daily production cost is 5,000 Ksh plus 20 Ksh per liter of milk produced. If the total cost one day was 9,400 Ksh, how many liters were produced?</p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    <me>9400 = 20L + 5000</me>
                    <me>4400 = 20L \text{ so } L = 220 \text{ liters}</me>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>
    </exercises>

    <xi:include href="../lesson-plan-templates/assessment-methods.ptx" />
    <xi:include href="../lesson-plan-templates/reflection.ptx"/>
</section>